For the data shared build a classification model using CNN and¶

Keras and perform below tasks.¶

• Plot the test and validation, loss and accuracy.

• Check for overfitting and apply L1, L2 regularisation, early stopping and dropout techniques.

• Plot the accuracy and loss with different optimizers.

• Fine tune hyperparameters using Keras tuner.

• Display confusion matrix

• Calculate accuracy, precision and recall

• Plot the ROC curve

• Chose the right threshold for sigmoid output.

Problem Statement:¶

  • To build a deep learning classification model using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) in Keras that can accurately identify whether a patient is suffering from pneumonia or not by analyzing chest X-ray images.

Objective:¶

1) The objective is to create an accurate and efficient model that can help improve the diagnosis of pneumonia, especially in regions where medical resources and personnel are limited.

2) The model should be evaluated based on various performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, and recall, and should be fine-tuned using Keras Tuner to obtain the best hyperparameters for the model.

3) Also the model should be evaluated for overfitting and appropriate techniques such as L1 or L2 regularization, early stopping, and dropout should be applied to prevent overfitting.

4) And then check the model's performance should be visualized using various plots, including ROC curves and confusion matrices, to help understand its strengths and weaknesses

There are two categories:-¶
  • NORMAL
  • PNEUMONIA

In [45]:
def process_data(img_dims, batch_size):
    train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, zoom_range=0.3, vertical_flip=True)
    test_val_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)
    
    train_gen = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=data+'/train', 
    target_size=(img_dims, img_dims), 
    batch_size=batch_size, 
    class_mode='binary', 
    shuffle=True)

    test_gen = test_val_datagen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=data+'/test', 
    target_size=(img_dims, img_dims), 
    batch_size=batch_size, 
    class_mode='binary', 
    shuffle=True)
    
    test_data = []
    test_labels = []

    for cond in ['/NORMAL/', '/PNEUMONIA/']:
        for img in (os.listdir(data + '/test' + cond)):
            img = plt.imread(data+'/test'+cond+img)
            img = cv2.resize(img, (img_dims, img_dims))
            img = np.dstack([img, img, img])
            img = img.astype('float32') / 255
            if cond=='/NORMAL/':
                label = 0
            elif cond=='/PNEUMONIA/':
                label = 1
            test_data.append(img)
            test_labels.append(label)
        
    test_data = np.array(test_data)
    test_labels = np.array(test_labels)
    
    return train_gen, test_gen, test_data, test_labels
  • target_size: is the size of input images, every image will be resized to this size.
  • color_mode: if the image is either black and white or grayscale set “grayscale” or if the image has three color channels, set “rgb”.
  • batch_size: No. of images to be yielded from the generator per batch.
  • class_mode: Set “binary” if you have only two classes to predict, if not set to“categorical”, in case if you’re developing an Autoencoder system, both input and the output would probably be the same image, for this case set to “input”.

In [47]:
inputs = Input(shape=(img_dims, img_dims, 3))

# 1st conv block
x = Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(inputs)
x = Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(x)

# 2nd conv block
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(x)

# 3rd conv block
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(x)

# 4th conv block
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = SeparableConv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
x = MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(x)
x = Dropout(rate=0.2)(x)

In [68]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix

preds = model.predict(test_data)

acc = accuracy_score(test_labels, np.round(preds))*100
cm = confusion_matrix(test_labels, np.round(preds))
tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()

print('CONFUSION MATRIX')
print(cm)

print('\nTEST METRICS')
precision = tp/(tp+fp)*100
recall = tp/(tp+fn)*100
print('Accuracy: {}%'.format(acc))
print('Precision: {}%'.format(precision))
print('Recall: {}%'.format(recall))
print('F1-score: {}'.format(2*precision*recall/(precision+recall)))

print('\nTRAIN METRIC')
print('Train acc: {}'.format(np.round((history.history['accuracy'][-1])*100, 2)))
